{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01K5xoVF9KjksCruexACq5XU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me do a quick self-review of my changes before calling the code-review-expert.\n\n1. **Implementation Completeness**: The logic is fully implemented, no stubs.\n\n2. **Code Quality**: The patterns look consistent with existing code - same `.split(/(\\s+)/)` pattern, same `seen.has/add` deduplication.\n\n3. **Integration & Refactoring**: The `normalizeErraticCasing` function normalizes erratic casing per-word. But `hasErraticCasing` is called on both the full text and individual tokens in `normalizeErraticCasing`. Let me check - in `normalizeErraticCasing`, it calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` on individual tokens (words), which is correct since `hasErraticCasing` uses `split(/\\s+/)` and `.some()`. For a single token with no spaces, it would check that single token. \n\nThat seems fine.\n\n4. **Consolidation**: The `applyBlindOcrRepair` function is still used in `normalizeOcrTitle`. The `generateBlindOcrVariants` delegates to it, which is good.\n\n5. **Codebase Consistency**: Are there other places where OCR repair is done that should use `generateBlindOcrVariants`? The `normalizeOcrTitle` function at line ~870 still uses `applyBlindOcrRepair` directly - that seems intentional since it's for final output normalization, not candidate generation. I'm noticing the `hasErraticCasing` check in `normalizeErraticCasing` might have an edge case I should verify.\n\nLooking at how `hasErraticCasing` is called on individual tokens versus the full line text - when it's applied to a single token, it correctly checks just that word, but I want to make sure the distinction between testing `line.text` for the artifact pattern versus `singleText` for the actual repair is intentional and consistent with the original logic. repaired `singleText`.\n\nWait, let me re-read - the condition is:\n```\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n```\n\nBut then:\n```\nlet repairable = singleText;\nif (hasErraticCasing(repairable)) {\n```\n\nSo we check `hasErraticCasing(line.text)` for the condition, but then check `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` (which is `singleText` = repaired version). The erratic casing check on `line.text` triggers the block, but then the inner check is on `singleText`. If `repairOcrText` somehow fixed the erratic casing, the inner check would fail and we'd just fall through to `generateBlindOcrVariants` on an unchanged `repairable`. That seems fine, actually - we're checking the original text to decide whether to enter the block, then working with the repaired version inside. I think the logic is consistent with the original pattern, so I'll move forward with running the code review.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":308,"cache_read_input_tokens":28549,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":308},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"819657b8-6f44-46cc-8dc5-0c4609d302a1","uuid":"071232d2-269d-46d1-83fd-72ba51e93d64"}
