{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0137ayiYAPPX38LPZDkCyvxJ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all the information needed. Here are the specific issues found:\n\n---\n\n**Issue 1 — `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` on a single token, which will never match**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 893.\n\n`hasErraticCasing` splits on `\\s+` and checks `.some(word => ...)`. When called with a single token (no whitespace), the split produces one element and the check works correctly — but the token passed at line 893 is already one element from a `split(/(\\s+)/)` at line 890. That part is fine.\n\nThe actual bug is different: `normalizeErraticCasing` skips `isAllCaps` tokens at line 892, then on line 893 calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` — but `hasErraticCasing` also skips `isAllCaps` words internally (line 881). So for an `isAllCaps` token the guard at line 892 is redundant, not wrong. However, `hasErraticCasing` counts uppercase letters in `inner = word.slice(1)` and requires `upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`. This means a word like `KoPyTka` (5 uppercase inner chars, 1 lowercase inner char) passes — that is the stated goal. But a word like `KoPytka` (2 uppercase inner, 4 lowercase inner: `2 >= 4 * 0.3 = 1.2` — passes) will also be normalized, which appears correct. No bug here.\n\n**Issue 2 — `isAllCaps` check in `generateBlindOcrVariants` operates on the full multi-word string, diverging from `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s own per-token logic**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 907–909 and 915–928.\n\n`applyBlindOcrRepair` (lines 847–875) uses `isAllCaps(text)` at the top level to pick a whole-string strategy. `generateBlindOcrVariants` does the same at line 907. But `applyBlindOcrRepair` also re-checks `isAllCaps(token)` per token in its mixed-case branch (line 864), applying the all-caps digit substitutions to all-caps tokens within a mixed-case string.\n\nThe `iVariant` branch in `generateBlindOcrVariants` (lines 915–928) duplicates this per-token logic identically to `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s mixed-case branch, except it substitutes `1 → i` instead of `1 → l`. The duplication is a maintenance hazard: `applyBlindOcrRepair` has substitutions for `¡`, `€` but not `4→A` or `5→S` in the mixed-case branch, and the `iVariant` block mirrors this inconsistency. If `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s mixed-case branch gains a new substitution in the future, `iVariant` will silently diverge. The two should share the per-token pipeline with the `1` substitution target as a parameter.\n\n**Issue 3 — The `seen` deduplication guard at line 677 compares against `singleText` but `repairable` may have already changed it**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 675–683.\n\nAfter the erratic-casing branch (lines 665–673), `repairable` may be a different string from `singleText`. Line 677 correctly guards `variant !== singleText && variant !== repairable`, so variants equal to either are skipped. But the `seen` set at this point already contains `singleText.toLowerCase()` (added at line 653) and may also contain `repairable.toLowerCase()` (added at line 669 if it passed). The explicit `!= singleText && != repairable` guards are therefore redundant with the `seen` check on line 678, creating two separate deduplication mechanisms that must stay in sync. The explicit string equality guards could be removed — the `seen` set is the authoritative deduplication and already covers them.\n\n**Issue 4 — `normalizeOcrTitle` title-case condition is inverted**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 965.\n\n```typescript\nif (text !== beforeSub && isAllCaps(text)) {\n  text = toTitleCase(text);\n}\n```\n\nThe comment at line 963 says \"ONLY when OCR substitution changed the text\" to \"preserve clean ALL_CAPS titles\". But the actual condition applies title-casing only when the text *is* all-caps after substitution. A clean all-caps title like `\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"` has no digits, so `applyBlindOcrRepair` returns it unchanged (`text === beforeSub`), and the condition is false — so it is preserved. That is correct.\n\nHowever: consider `\"CH0COLATE CAKE\"` — `applyBlindOcrRepair` changes it to `\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"` (still all-caps), `text !== beforeSub` is true, `isAllCaps(text)` is true, so it gets title-cased to `\"Chocolate Cake\"`. This matches the stated intent. But `\"KoPyTka Z 0liwkami\"` — `applyBlindOcrRepair` changes `0` to `O`, result is `\"KoPyTka Z Oliwkami\"`, which is *not* all-caps, so `isAllCaps` is false and no title-casing is applied, leaving `\"KoPyTka Z Oliwkami\"` as the output. `normalizeOcrTitle` never calls `normalizeErraticCasing`. This is not a bug in the new diff specifically, but the new functions do not compose into `normalizeOcrTitle`, creating an inconsistency: erratic casing is fixed in `buildCandidates` but not in the post-selection normalization path.\n\n**Issue 5 — `hasErraticCasing` threshold `upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` is asymmetric with its inverse**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 885.\n\nA word like `KoPytka` has `inner = oPytka`, `upperInner = 1` (`P`), `lowerInner = 5`. `1 >= 5 * 0.3 = 1.5` — false. So `KoPytka` does NOT trigger erratic casing, only `KoPYtka` (`upperInner = 2`, `2 >= 4 * 0.3 = 1.2` — true) does. The 30% threshold means a word needs roughly 1 uppercase for every 3 lowercase inner chars. This is a design choice, but the comment says \"e.g. `KoPyTka`\" which has `upperInner = 2`, `lowerInner = 3`, ratio `2 >= 0.9` — passes. The docstring example is consistent with the threshold. No bug, but the minimum `upperInner >= 2` guard (line 885, left side of `&&`) combined with the `word.length < 3` early exit means two-character words are never flagged, which could miss `aB` patterns. This is almost certainly intentional for noise reduction and is acceptable.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of actionable items:**\n\n1. (Medium) `generateBlindOcrVariants` duplicates `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s per-token transformation logic for the `iVariant` branch. Extract a shared helper that accepts the `1 → ?` substitution target to eliminate drift.\n\n2. (Low) The explicit `variant !== singleText && variant !== repairable` guards at line 677 are redundant with the `seen` set. Remove them to have a single deduplication path.\n\n3. (Medium) `normalizeOcrTitle` does not call `normalizeErraticCasing`, so a title selected from a non-erratic-casing path will exit with erratic casing intact. Either add the normalization step in `normalizeOcrTitle` or document explicitly why it is excluded there (e.g. because `buildCandidates` already emits the corrected variant as a separate candidate)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2414973a3759bc46 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 18310\ntool_uses: 8\nduration_ms: 66377</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"819657b8-6f44-46cc-8dc5-0c4609d302a1","uuid":"a8cc3ec1-849d-4016-b7d2-b562566f8f27","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the following changes to `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. Focus on:\n\n1. Implementation completeness — no stubs or placeholder logic\n2. Code quality and consistency with surrounding patterns\n3. Whether similar/related functions should be consolidated\n4. Whether other parts of the codebase should be updated\n\nThe diff adds:\n- `hasErraticCasing(text)` — detects words with mixed uppercase inner chars (e.g. `KoPyTka`)\n- `normalizeErraticCasing(text)` — title-cases erratically-cased tokens\n- `generateBlindOcrVariants(text)` — produces both `1→i` and `1→l` candidates (vs single variant before)\n- Updated `buildCandidates` block to use all three new functions\n\nRead the relevant sections of the file before reviewing:\n- Lines 658–700 (updated buildCandidates block)\n- Lines 860–960 (new functions + normalizeOcrTitle)\n\nReport specific issues only — skip praise or generic observations.","agentId":"a2414973a3759bc46","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all the information needed. Here are the specific issues found:\n\n---\n\n**Issue 1 — `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` on a single token, which will never match**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 893.\n\n`hasErraticCasing` splits on `\\s+` and checks `.some(word => ...)`. When called with a single token (no whitespace), the split produces one element and the check works correctly — but the token passed at line 893 is already one element from a `split(/(\\s+)/)` at line 890. That part is fine.\n\nThe actual bug is different: `normalizeErraticCasing` skips `isAllCaps` tokens at line 892, then on line 893 calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` — but `hasErraticCasing` also skips `isAllCaps` words internally (line 881). So for an `isAllCaps` token the guard at line 892 is redundant, not wrong. However, `hasErraticCasing` counts uppercase letters in `inner = word.slice(1)` and requires `upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`. This means a word like `KoPyTka` (5 uppercase inner chars, 1 lowercase inner char) passes — that is the stated goal. But a word like `KoPytka` (2 uppercase inner, 4 lowercase inner: `2 >= 4 * 0.3 = 1.2` — passes) will also be normalized, which appears correct. No bug here.\n\n**Issue 2 — `isAllCaps` check in `generateBlindOcrVariants` operates on the full multi-word string, diverging from `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s own per-token logic**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 907–909 and 915–928.\n\n`applyBlindOcrRepair` (lines 847–875) uses `isAllCaps(text)` at the top level to pick a whole-string strategy. `generateBlindOcrVariants` does the same at line 907. But `applyBlindOcrRepair` also re-checks `isAllCaps(token)` per token in its mixed-case branch (line 864), applying the all-caps digit substitutions to all-caps tokens within a mixed-case string.\n\nThe `iVariant` branch in `generateBlindOcrVariants` (lines 915–928) duplicates this per-token logic identically to `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s mixed-case branch, except it substitutes `1 → i` instead of `1 → l`. The duplication is a maintenance hazard: `applyBlindOcrRepair` has substitutions for `¡`, `€` but not `4→A` or `5→S` in the mixed-case branch, and the `iVariant` block mirrors this inconsistency. If `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s mixed-case branch gains a new substitution in the future, `iVariant` will silently diverge. The two should share the per-token pipeline with the `1` substitution target as a parameter.\n\n**Issue 3 — The `seen` deduplication guard at line 677 compares against `singleText` but `repairable` may have already changed it**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 675–683.\n\nAfter the erratic-casing branch (lines 665–673), `repairable` may be a different string from `singleText`. Line 677 correctly guards `variant !== singleText && variant !== repairable`, so variants equal to either are skipped. But the `seen` set at this point already contains `singleText.toLowerCase()` (added at line 653) and may also contain `repairable.toLowerCase()` (added at line 669 if it passed). The explicit `!= singleText && != repairable` guards are therefore redundant with the `seen` check on line 678, creating two separate deduplication mechanisms that must stay in sync. The explicit string equality guards could be removed — the `seen` set is the authoritative deduplication and already covers them.\n\n**Issue 4 — `normalizeOcrTitle` title-case condition is inverted**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 965.\n\n```typescript\nif (text !== beforeSub && isAllCaps(text)) {\n  text = toTitleCase(text);\n}\n```\n\nThe comment at line 963 says \"ONLY when OCR substitution changed the text\" to \"preserve clean ALL_CAPS titles\". But the actual condition applies title-casing only when the text *is* all-caps after substitution. A clean all-caps title like `\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"` has no digits, so `applyBlindOcrRepair` returns it unchanged (`text === beforeSub`), and the condition is false — so it is preserved. That is correct.\n\nHowever: consider `\"CH0COLATE CAKE\"` — `applyBlindOcrRepair` changes it to `\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"` (still all-caps), `text !== beforeSub` is true, `isAllCaps(text)` is true, so it gets title-cased to `\"Chocolate Cake\"`. This matches the stated intent. But `\"KoPyTka Z 0liwkami\"` — `applyBlindOcrRepair` changes `0` to `O`, result is `\"KoPyTka Z Oliwkami\"`, which is *not* all-caps, so `isAllCaps` is false and no title-casing is applied, leaving `\"KoPyTka Z Oliwkami\"` as the output. `normalizeOcrTitle` never calls `normalizeErraticCasing`. This is not a bug in the new diff specifically, but the new functions do not compose into `normalizeOcrTitle`, creating an inconsistency: erratic casing is fixed in `buildCandidates` but not in the post-selection normalization path.\n\n**Issue 5 — `hasErraticCasing` threshold `upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` is asymmetric with its inverse**\n\n`/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, line 885.\n\nA word like `KoPytka` has `inner = oPytka`, `upperInner = 1` (`P`), `lowerInner = 5`. `1 >= 5 * 0.3 = 1.5` — false. So `KoPytka` does NOT trigger erratic casing, only `KoPYtka` (`upperInner = 2`, `2 >= 4 * 0.3 = 1.2` — true) does. The 30% threshold means a word needs roughly 1 uppercase for every 3 lowercase inner chars. This is a design choice, but the comment says \"e.g. `KoPyTka`\" which has `upperInner = 2`, `lowerInner = 3`, ratio `2 >= 0.9` — passes. The docstring example is consistent with the threshold. No bug, but the minimum `upperInner >= 2` guard (line 885, left side of `&&`) combined with the `word.length < 3` early exit means two-character words are never flagged, which could miss `aB` patterns. This is almost certainly intentional for noise reduction and is acceptable.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of actionable items:**\n\n1. (Medium) `generateBlindOcrVariants` duplicates `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s per-token transformation logic for the `iVariant` branch. Extract a shared helper that accepts the `1 → ?` substitution target to eliminate drift.\n\n2. (Low) The explicit `variant !== singleText && variant !== repairable` guards at line 677 are redundant with the `seen` set. Remove them to have a single deduplication path.\n\n3. (Medium) `normalizeOcrTitle` does not call `normalizeErraticCasing`, so a title selected from a non-erratic-casing path will exit with erratic casing intact. Either add the normalization step in `normalizeOcrTitle` or document explicitly why it is excluded there (e.g. because `buildCandidates` already emits the corrected variant as a separate candidate)."}],"totalDurationMs":66377,"totalTokens":18310,"totalToolUseCount":8,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":281,"cache_read_input_tokens":15939,"output_tokens":2089,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":281},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
